      commentary: `When Arjuna asks what forces a person to act wrongly — against their own better judgment — Krishna's answer is direct: kāma. Desire in its compulsive form. And when desire is frustrated, krodha: anger. Both arise from rajas — the quality of restless, hungry, agitated energy. And together they are mahāśana — all-consuming.\n\nThis is your real enemy. Not a person. Not a circumstance. Not an external adversary. The enemy is within, and it lives in the gap between what you have and what you want. Every destructive act in human history can be traced back to this: desire that was not examined, anger that was not understood.\n\nKrishna uses the word viddhi — know this. Not destroy it. Not suppress it. Know it. Recognise it. See it clearly for what it is when it arises. Because what you can see clearly has less power over you than what operates in the dark. The enemy becomes less dangerous when you know its face.`,
