      commentary: `Desire is described here as an insatiable fire — and the metaphor is precise. What do you feed a fire when you want it to go out? Nothing. You starve it. But what most people do with desire is feed it: give it what it wants, expecting satisfaction, and discover instead that it only wants more. The fire that you feed grows larger.\n\nThe verse adds something crucial: this desire covers knowledge — even the knowledge of the wise. This is why intelligent people make obviously destructive choices. It is not lack of knowledge. It is that the desire, in the moment, simply obscures what is known. The clarity is there — underneath. But it is buried under the immediate heat of wanting.\n\nThis is why practices of stillness — meditation, reflection, space between stimulus and response — are not luxuries. They are the conditions under which your actual wisdom can be accessed. Without them, you are operating with your knowledge covered. With them, you can see clearly enough to choose differently.`,
