      commentary: `The sequence matters: senses first, then the enemy. You do not go directly for the desire in the abstract. You start at the most concrete, most accessible level — the senses. Withdraw their access to the objects that feed the compulsive desire. Create the conditions in which the mind has a chance to settle and the intellect a chance to clear.\n\nJñāna-vijñāna-nāśanam — the destroyer of both knowledge and realisation. These are two different things: jñāna is knowledge in the intellectual sense, the understanding of the teaching. Vijñāna is realised knowledge — not just knowing the concept but having it penetrate to the level of lived experience. Desire destroys both. It confuses the intellect and prevents the direct experience of what the intellect understands.\n\nThe call to slay the enemy is not a call to hatred of desire. It is a call to freedom from it. You are not fighting desire with anger but with clarity — with the calm, determined action of someone who understands what they are dealing with and chooses, from their deepest centre, to no longer be ruled by it.`
