      commentary: `A hierarchy is laid out: matter → senses → mind → intellect → Self. Each level is subtler and more pervasive than the one below it. The senses are subtler than gross matter — they can perceive without physical contact. The mind is subtler than the senses — it can operate without immediate sensory input, in memory and imagination. The intellect is subtler than the mind — it can observe and evaluate the mind's operations. And the Self is subtler than all of them — it is the pure awareness within which all of these function.\n\nThis hierarchy is practical, not merely theoretical. It tells you where to go when you need to override desire. You cannot fight desire at the level of desire. You go up. You engage the mind to override the senses. You engage the intellect to oversee the mind. And when even the intellect is compromised by desire, you go to the level of the Self — the witnessing awareness that is prior to all of it — and operate from there.\n\nThis is the ultimate tool: not willpower, not discipline, not ritual — but identity. When you know yourself as the Self rather than as the bundle of desires and reactions, you are operating from a level that desire cannot touch. The final verse of the chapter will make this explicit.`,
